<DOC><DOCNO> AP880715-0241 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-15-88 0258EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlight 1stAdd   07-15 0498</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlight, 1st Add,0526</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House Ways and Means Committee hasapproved a bill correcting errors in the 1986 tax overhaul, aftertacking on a fistful of special-interest benefits and the taxincreases to pay for them.   Pipe smokers, some farmers and moonlighters accustomed towriting off part of their telephone bills would pay more.   The bill endorsed Thursday could provide $7.1 billion of taxcuts over the next three years and raise an equal amount to financethem.</TEXT><DATELINE>MARION, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan is promising farmers in thecountry's drought-stricken midsection that he would do everythingto help America cope with the ``worst natural disaster since theDust Bowl of the 1930s.''   At the same time, he called on Congress to ``act quickly'' on apackage of legislation aimed at making emergency federal aidavailable to farmers.   Reagan used his tour Thursday to announce that he wasdispatching Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng on a tour of severalstates hard hit by the dry spell.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Three of the nation's biggest banking companies have reportedprofits in the second quarter after posting losses a year earlier.   Chemical Banking Corp., Security Pacific Corp. and Bank of NewYork Co. _ had sustained heavy losses in the second quarter of 1987from writeoffs for potential losses on loans to developingcountries.   First City Bancorp. of Texas, meanwhile, which recently receiveda $970 million federal bailout, reported net income of $17.2million for the 72-day period immediately following its $1.6billion reorganization.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Oil prices have risen sharply and partly erasedsteep losses from earlier this week, but traders attributed therebound to short-term influences and Saudi Arabia's denial that itwas boosting production.   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Thursday, the near-monthcontract for West Texas Intermediate crude advanced 32 cents perbarrel from its 21-month low to close at $14.76.   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesaleunleaded gasoline rose .06 cent a gallon to 50.54 cents, and No. 2heating oil rose .77 cent a gallon to 40.91 cents.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Democrat Lloyd Bentsen, back in the Senateafter a campaign trip, says running for vice president will notdistract him from pushing for final approval of a wide-rangingtrade bill.   The House approved a revised trade bill Wednesday and sent it tothe Senate, where action could follow next week's break for theDemocratic National Convention.   Some Democrats are saying the decision by Massachusetts Gov.Michael Dukakis to tap Bentsen as his running mate heightensprospects for Senate approval of the legislation.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Corn, oat and soybean prices rose Thursday on forecasts foranother month of drought conditions in the Midwest.   Stocks posted small gains. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials rose 9.25 to 2,113.62.   Bonds were mixed.   The dollar rose in advance of Friday's report on the nation'strade deficit. Gold prices fell.</TEXT></DOC>